{
  "text": "Our findings are consistent with the results reported by Costa et al, [CITATION_1] where older age was significantly associated with persistent/recurrent disease. A 2014 systematic review reported overall rates of AIS persistence/recurrence of 6-29%. 24 In a WA cohort of 338 patients treated for AIS from 2001 through 2012 with a median follow-up interval of 3.6 years, AIS persistence/recurrence was reported in 27 women (8%). [CITATION_2] Up to 55% of AIS cases may coexist with a high-grade squamous intraepithelial lesion. [CITATION_3] In the current study, pure AIS lesions (absence of coexistent CIN 2/3) detected incidentally on an excision specimen had an increased risk of disease persistence/recurrence when compared to mixed lesions (presence of coexistent CIN 2/3). This finding is notable and consistent with that of Song et al, [CITATION_4] who reported that patients diagnosed with a mixed cervical AIS lesion (CIN 2/3 present) following cone biopsy had a more favorable prognosis than patients with pure AIS. Original Research GYNECOLOGY ajog.org An important finding in our study was that an AIS lesion >8 mm in extent strongly correlated with persistence/ recurrence. Consistent with the Canadian guidelines, [CITATION_5] our findings suggest that smaller incidental AIS lesions (<8 mm) with clear margins do not require repeated excision, although this requires validation in larger prospective studies. Lesion size was recorded in only 51% of patients in our study because it is not mandatory for pathologists in Australia to report this. Prospective inclusion of AIS lesion size in excisional biopsy specimens would likely enhance our understanding of persistence/recurrence risk and inform future management guidelines. There were no significant differences in AIS persistence/recurrence by socioeconomic status, specimen depth, or treatment modality (CKC vs LEEP).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "32728950",
    "[CITATION_2]": "28598182",
